answers.body_markdown:
You&#39;ll need to use:

- `google.script.run.withSuccessHandler` which is a JavaScript, asynchronous, [Client-side API](https://developers.google.com/apps-script/guides/html/reference/run) that allows you to interact with server side functions (references could be found [here](https://developers.google.com/apps-script/guides/html/communication)).
- `setInterval` function to invoke the aforementioned client-side API at a frequency you see fit
   - 3000/3500 milliseconds is what I&#39;ve been using so far and the [service quotas](https://developers.google.com/apps-script/guides/services/quotas) don&#39;t specifically talk about *its* limitations

Server side
===========
This is pretty much the code that gets written in the **code.gs** part of the script; where all your functions reside that interact perhaps with your Spreadsheets or act as the webhook

Client side
===========
That&#39;s the code that runs from your ***.html** file and, post loading, on your web browser. This is where you get to use the &quot;asynchronous&quot; API

Example
=======
In my [dummy setup](https://script.google.com/macros/s/AKfycbzm_yn_6Vsllcn6PTBfpCj0fOPUeVKkg3jWLo8CJ3v797cRgSd6/exec), I&#39;m -

1. Fetching random quotes from [thesimpsonsquoteapi](https://thesimpsonsquoteapi.glitch.me)
2. Displaying a timer that changes every second

Code.gs (server-side code)
--------------------------
```
function doGet(e) {
  return HtmlService.createHtmlOutputFromFile(&#39;Index&#39;).setTitle(&#39;Realtime Data&#39;);
}

function randomQuotes() {
  var baseURL = &#39;https://thesimpsonsquoteapi.glitch.me/quotes&#39;;
  var quotesData = UrlFetchApp.fetch(baseURL, { muteHttpExceptions: true });
  var quote;
  var imageURL;
  if (quotesData.getResponseCode() == 200 || quotesData.getResponseCode() == 201) {
    var response = quotesData.getContentText();
    var data = JSON.parse(response)[0];
    quote = data[&quot;quote&quot;];
    imageURL = data[&quot;image&quot;];
  } else {
    quote = &#39;Random Quote Generator is broken!&#39;;
    imageURL = &#39;https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/1061/1924/products/Sad_Face_Emoji_large.png?v=1480481055&#39;;
  }
  var randomQuote = {
    &quot;quote&quot;: quote,
    &quot;imageTag&quot;: &#39;&lt;img class=&quot;responsive-img&quot; src=&quot;&#39; + imageURL + &#39;&quot;&gt;&#39;
  }
  return randomQuote;
}

function getTime() {
  var now = new Date();
  return now;
}
```

Index.html (client-side code)
-----------------------------
*I&#39;m only highlighting the relevant aspects of the code*

The following fetches random quotes every 10 seconds (10000 ms)

```
&lt;script&gt;
    function onSuccess1(quotedata) {
        var quoteactual = document.getElementById(&#39;quote&#39;);
        quoteactual.innerhtml = quotedata.quote;
        var quoteimg = document.getElementById(&#39;quoteImage&#39;);
        quoteimg.innerhtml = quotedata.imagetag;
    }

    setInterval(function() {
        console.log(&quot;getting quote...&quot;)
        google.script.run.withSuccessHandler(onsuccess1).randomQuotes();
    }, 10000);
&lt;/script&gt;
```

This fetches time every 1 second (1000 ms)
```
&lt;script&gt;
    function onSuccess2(now) {
        var div = document.getElementById(&#39;time&#39;);
        var today = new Date();
        var time = today.getHours() + &quot; : &quot; + today.getMinutes() + &quot; : &quot; + today.getSeconds();
        div.innerhtml = time;
    }

    setInterval(function() {
        console.log(&quot;getting time...&quot;)
        google.script.run.withSuccessHandler(onsuccess2).getTime();
    }, 1000);
&lt;/script&gt;
```

You can access the entire script on [my github repository](https://github.com/schoraria911/google-apps-script/tree/master/Real-time%20Dashboard) or [make a copy from the original script](https://script.google.com/d/1vrW0lVEiAUvNqpVAKGZuI847grDsyv9aqJLNu07wusnCPzHdD_G-3JYn/edit?usp=sharing).

Output
------
The image here is supposed to change every 10s and timer, every 1s

[![real-time][1]][1]

The browser console log can be viewed here -

[![real-time console][2]][2]

I wrote [this article](https://script.gs/build-a-real-time-dashboard-web-app-using-google-script-run-api/) a couple weeks ago that outlines most aspects of what everyone has been answering/commenting so far but I&#39;m hoping my explanation here helps as well.


  [1]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/Ng99g.gif
  [2]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/BNnz9.gif

